126
00:06:39.070 --> 00:06:41.320
about what people's
performance is likely to be?

127
00:06:42.330 --> 00:06:45.500
In doing this,
there are a few things to bare in mind.

128
00:06:45.500 --> 00:06:46.200
Okay?

129
00:06:46.200 --> 00:06:49.520
First, the most obviously, you want
to be comparing apples with apples.

130
00:06:49.520 --> 00:06:53.920
So, if you're looking at differences in
performance, you want to make sure that

131
00:06:53.920 --> 00:06:58.320
people are doing the same work in
the same place, or at the same level.

132
00:06:58.320 --> 00:06:59.260
All of those sorts of things.

133
00:06:59.260 --> 00:07:01.940
You really want to hold that constant
because, otherwise, it's quite

134
00:07:01.940 --> 00:07:05.800
possible that what you're really seeing is
differences in what people are supposed to

135
00:07:05.800 --> 00:07:09.970
be doing rather than actually differences
in their attributes driving performance.

136
00:07:09.970 --> 00:07:14.160
A pernicious version of this is you
want to be very wary of time in the job.

137
00:07:14.160 --> 00:07:16.870
Generally, we expect certainly we
people have been in the job for

138
00:07:16.870 --> 00:07:19.560
a moderate period of time, they're going
to be better at what they are doing.

139
00:07:19.560 --> 00:07:23.840
So, are you really comparing people
new versus medium in the job, or

140
00:07:23.840 --> 00:07:27.080
are you comparing people who are all
in the same job at the same time?

141
00:07:27.080 --> 00:07:31.680
The second thing that you want to be
concerned about, and I'll get into this

